 1. usually it is better to use [**`get_user_model`** [Django-doc]](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/topics/auth/customizing/#django.contrib.auth.get_user_model) to refer to the user model, since you can later change your mind about it;
 2. You probably want to make `user` and `story` unique together, such that a user can not make two ratings for the *same* story;
 3. some databases, like PostgreSQL allow us to enforce range constraints at the database level, and thus make it more safe.

we thus can rewrite this to:

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;from django.db import models
from django.contrib.auth import &lt;b&gt;get_user_model&lt;/b&gt;
from django.db.models import CheckConstraint, Q, UniqueConstraint

class Rating(models.Model):
    rate = models.FloatField(validators=[MinValueValidator(0.0), MaxValueValidator(10.0)])
    story = models.ForeignKey(Story, on_delete=models.CASCADE)
    user = models.ForeignKey(&lt;b&gt;get_user_model()&lt;/b&gt;, on_delete=models.CASCADE)

    class Meta:
        constraints = [
            &lt;b&gt;CheckConstraint(check=Q(rate__range=(0, 10)), name=&#39;valid_rate&#39;)&lt;/b&gt;,
            &lt;b&gt;UniqueConstraint(fields=[&#39;user&#39;, &#39;story&#39;], name=&#39;rating_once&#39;)&lt;/b&gt;
        ]&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

